Hello here 👋 
I am using the DCE with docker on a GNU/Linux OS, the challenge right now is that whatever I set after `-o` is defined as folders and it does not change the filename.
e.g. `-o communityhighlights/output` creates folder `communityhighlights` and folder `output` and then leaves at long name for the html file.

Any ideas? Thanks!

Hi. Yeah, the `-o` option won't do much in Docker. You have to instead change the volume binding between the container's file system and the host's file system. More info here: https://github.com/Tyrrrz/DiscordChatExporter/wiki/Docker-usage-instructions

embeds.title: Docker usage instructions · Tyrrrz/DiscordChatExporter Wiki
embeds.description: Exports Discord chat logs to a file. Contribute to Tyrrrz/DiscordChatExporter development by creating an account on GitHub.

messages.content:
In other words, change the `/path/on/machine` in this example:

```
docker run --rm -v /path/on/machine:/app/out tyrrrz/discordchatexporter:stable export -t TOKEN -c CHANNELID
```

I shouldn't have said `-o` won't _do much_ in Docker. It will still be useful if you want to change the file name or create a specific directory structure, you just have to remember that it's inside the container's virtual file system that you also have to bind to some physical place in your host's file system.

Thank you for your answer.

This is the command I am using
`docker run --rm -it -e DISCORD_TOKEN_BOT=TRUE -v $PWD:/app/out tyrrrz/discordchatexporter:stable export -t BOTTOKEN -c CHANNELID --filter user -o communityhighlights --media --reuse-media`

The thing is that during the export it is creating a directory called `communityhighlights` but it is not calling the file `communityhighlights.html` as expected in `$PWD`

Yeah that's because when you provide an output path without extension (in this case `communityhighlights`), it assumes it's a directory. The `-o` option works with both file and directory paths. Try setting it to `communityhighlights.html` instead.
